• Big blockers / likely crashes

  - R/model.R:27 unconditionally does info2 <- secondOrder$info. When there’s no higher-order part (parTableO2 == NULL), secondOrder is NULL (see specifySubModel()), so this will error. This also cascades into R/model.R:65/:69 where you union(..., info2$...).
  - R/mcpls.R:38-40 writes into fit.sim$firstStage$..., but the new model shape uses submodels$firstOrder/submodels$secondOrder. Also line R/mcpls.R:39 computes cova(fit.sim$data) even though you just wrote to fit.sim$firstStage$data. This looks broken for MCPLS.
  - R/djikstra_correction.R:117-126:
      - isHigherOrderComposite[[lv]] will error if model$info$isHigherOrderComposite is NULL (or missing).
      - diag(S.ii)[idx] <- rel[idx] does not modify S.ii (it modifies a temporary vector). If the goal is to alter the diagonal, you need a diag(S.ii) <- ... style replacement.

  Higher-order logic / correctness risks

  - R/pls.R:362-364 overwrites all secondOrder$data[, want] with first-order scores. If the second-order model includes any observed covariates (e.g. a structural OV that became .TEMP_OV__... via parseModelArguments()), those columns will be in want but not in scores, so scores[,
    want] will error. Safer: only overwrite intersect(want, colnames(scores)).
  - R/predict.R:110-112 computes L.ov <- ... but then uses t(L) (not t(L.ov)) to get X.cont.pred. For higher-order fits, L contains extra “LV-as-indicator” rows; using full L likely makes X.cont.pred include non-observed variables and can break benchmarking/ordered handling.
  - R/utils_higher_order.R:208 and R/utils_higher_order.R:217 have a typo in the keep-condition: lhs %in% lvs & lhs %in% lvs probably meant lhs %in% lvs & rhs %in% lvs. As-is, your filtering of lower-order ~~ parameters is wrong.
  - R/utils_higher_order.R:58-60 sets info2 <- firstOrder$info (should be secondOrder$info). Even if currently unused, it’s a footgun.
  - R/utils_higher_order.R:21-43 “multilevel keep” logic:
      - padStrO1 looks like a typo (parStrO1), and parStrO1 is never actually merged into parTableO1. If MLM syntax is expected to survive the split, it currently doesn’t.

  API/doc/test hygiene issues

  - R/pls.R:257 adds reliabilities to the signature, but there’s no roxygen @param reliabilities docs (will show up as undocumented arg in checks).
  - Tests are currently more like interactive scripts than testthat tests:
      - tests/testthat/test_higher_order.R:3+ runs devtools::load_all(), uses library(mvtnorm), and simulates N <- 100000L with no test_that()/expect_*(). This will be very slow and likely fail on CI/CRAN (and mvtnorm isn’t in Suggests).
      - tests/testthat/test_oneint.R:1+ also calls devtools::load_all() and library(cSEM) (not in Suggests), and prints objects rather than asserting.
  - Naming: the custom operator %|<->|% in R/model.R:8 is clever but hard to grep/read; isTRUE(x) || isTRUE(y) might be clearer/safer (and avoids treating non-TRUE truthy values unexpectedly).

  If you want, I can propose a small patch that (1) fixes the no-higher-order crash in specifyModel(), (2) fixes the diag(S.ii) reliability bug, and (3) makes higher-order pls_predict() use only observed-indicator loadings.
